HRMS Timesheet Feature - Study Guide & Client Decisions
Date: March 9, 2026 (UPDATED POST-MEETING)
 Purpose: Complete reference with all client decisions from March 6 meeting

PART 1: FEATURE OVERVIEW SUMMARY (UPDATED)
What is the Timesheet System?
A time tracking and balance management system for restaurant/gastro employees that:
Logs daily work hours and absences (simplified: Work/Free only)
Calculates vacation days, overtime, and compensations
Ensures Swiss labor law compliance
Provides views for both employees and managers
Admin categorizes absence types (not employee)
The Three Main Components (WITH CHANGES)
1️⃣ My View (Employee Interface) ✅ UPDATED
Personal time tracking dashboard
Log work hours OR Free day (no absence type selection)
DELETED: Timer feature (play/pause/stop)
View own vacation & overtime balance
Cannot edit balances (admin only)
Export personal timesheet
Key Data:
Work hours + breaks
Vacation days earned & used
Overtime accumulated
No manual balance adjustments
2️⃣ Team View (Manager Interface) ✅ UPDATED
See all employees' timesheets (or filter to one)
View team-wide balance overview
Edit individual employee balances
Approve/categorize "Free" entries (select absence type)
Export team reports (PDF/Excel)
Key Features:
Filter by employee
Show/hide former employees
2-tab balance management (Carryover, Payout only)
DELETED: Manual Adjustment tab
3️⃣ Company Settings (Admin Interface) ✅ UPDATED
Configure working hours (8h daily, 40h weekly, 48h max)
Set premium rates (Sunday 50%, Holiday 100%, Extratime 25%)
DELETED: Night Shift Premium (22:00-06:00)
Manage holidays (Swiss public + company-specific)
Configure vacation rules (age-based entitlements, pro-rata)
UPDATED: Carryover ALWAYS ON (no toggle)

PART 2: KEY CONCEPTS & CALCULATION FLOWS (VERIFIED)
Concept 1: Target Hours (Soll) ✅ CONFIRMED
What it is: How many hours an employee SHOULD work in a period
Calculation:
Target Hours = Working Days × 8h × Work Percentage

Example (Max Müller, December 2025):
- Working days in Dec: 23 (31 - weekends - 11 holidays)
- Daily target: 8h
- Work percentage: 100%
- Target = 23 × 8 × 100% = 184h

Pro-Rata for mid-year starters:
Employee starts June 1, 100% workload:
- Days remaining: 214 (June 1 - Dec 31)
- Target hours: 214 ÷ 365 × (52 weeks × 40h) = ~1,210h for rest of year


Concept 2: Worked Hours (Ist) ✅ CONFIRMED
What it is: Actual hours an employee worked + paid absences (unpaid ≠ included)
Includes:
✅ Actual work hours (logged in timesheet)
✅ Paid absences (vacation, sick, maternity, holiday premium)
✅ Premium hours (Sunday 50%, Holiday 100%, Extratime 25%)
Excludes:
❌ Unpaid absences (no hours, no pay, no balance impact)
❌ Free days (unpaid = 0 hours)
Example:
December 2025 for Max Müller:
Dec 1: 8h work
Dec 2: 8.5h work
Dec 3: 4h work + 4h sick (paid = counts)
Dec 3: 2h unpaid leave (0 hours, doesn't count)
...
Worked Hours = 180.5h (unpaid excluded)


Concept 3: Overtime Balance (Saldo) ✅ CONFIRMED
Formula:
Overtime = Worked Hours - Target Hours + Carryover - Compensation Used - Payouts

Example:
Worked: 183.2h
Target: 176.0h
Difference: +7.2h
Carryover from 2024: +5.0h
Compensation days used: -16h (2 days × 8h)
Payouts: -10.0h

Balance = 7.2 + 5.0 - 16 - 10 = -13.8h (owes company)

NO Manual Adjustments ❌ DELETED
Risk too high
Payouts cover most cases

Concept 4: Vacation Balance ✅ CONFIRMED
Formula:
Vacation = Earned Days + Carryover (100%, no limit) - Used Days - Payouts

Example (Max Müller, Age 35):
Annual entitlement: 25 days (age 20-49)
Earned since Jan 1: 20.8 days
Carryover from 2024: +5.0 days (100%, always allowed)
Used in 2025: -17 days
Payouts: -2.5 days

Balance = 20.8 + 5.0 - 17 - 2.5 = 6.3 days

CHANGE: Carryover NOW ALWAYS ENABLED
❌ OLD: Had toggle + max limit (5 days)
✅ NEW: Always 100% carryover, no system limit
Manual expiry (March 31) not enforced

Concept 5: Pro-Rata Calculations ✅ CONFIRMED
When used:
Employee starts mid-year
Employee works part-time (any %)
Combination of both
Example (Anna Schmidt, started June 1, 2025, 80% part-time, age 29):
Full-time entitlement: 25 days (age 20-49)
Work percentage: 80%
Days remaining in year (June-Dec): 214 days

Calculation:
1. Remaining fraction: 214 / 365 = 0.586
2. Pro-rated full-time: 25 × 0.586 = 14.65 days
3. Adjusted for part-time: 14.65 × 0.80 = 11.7 days earned in 2025

Apply work percentage history: Track if % changes mid-year
- Example: 80% (Jan-June) then 100% (July-Dec)
- Recalculate split at change date

CRITICAL: Work percentage history must be tracked (NEW database table)

Concept 6: Premium Hours ✅ UPDATED
Types KEPT:
Sunday Premium (50%) - Working on Sunday = +50% bonus hours
Holiday Premium (100%) - Working on public holiday = +100% bonus hours
Extratime Premium (25%) - Working >48h/week = +25% bonus hours
Type DELETED: ❌ Night Shift Premium (22:00-06:00) - REMOVED
Too complex for current use case
Can be added in Phase 2 if needed
Example (Week with Sunday work):
Mon-Fri: 40h work
Sunday: 8h work (on weekend)

Base hours: 48h
Sunday premium: 8h × 50% = 4h
Total: 48 + 4 = 52h

Status: ⚠️ EXTRATIME (exceeds 48h legal limit)
Action needed: Grant compensation day

Premium Stacking:
Sunday + Holiday: Both apply = 8 + 4 + 8 = 20h total
Premiums CAN stack

Concept 7: Weekly Compliance ✅ CONFIRMED
Status Levels:
✅ OK (≤40h) - Within standard hours
⚠️ OVERTIME (40-48h) - Exceeds standard but legal (0% premium)
🔴 EXTRATIME (>48h) - Illegal, requires 25% premium + compensation
Why it matters: Swiss labor law - max 48h/week average

